title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p><fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(\Longleftarrow )]]></fr:tex> Any submodule of a free module over an integral domain is torsion-free.</fr:p>
<fr:p><fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(\Longrightarrow )]]></fr:tex> Assume <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex> is torsion-free. Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> be the set of all linearly-independent subsets of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex>. We can check that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> is nonempty (since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex> being torsion-free and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> being an integral domain that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\{m\}]]></fr:tex> is linearly independent for any <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m\in  M]]></fr:tex> nonzero <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m\neq 0]]></fr:tex>) and all ascending chains in <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> admit an upper bound. Then by <fr:link
type="local"
href="zorn's-lemma.xml"
addr="zorn's-lemma"
title="Zorn's lemma">Zorn's lemma</fr:link> there exists a maximal element in <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>. That is to say, there exists a maximal free submodule <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p>We claim that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[M/F]]></fr:tex> is torsion. If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m+F\in  M]]></fr:tex> is not torsion, then the submodule <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[Rm+F]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex> is free and it properly contains <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[F]]></fr:tex>. Since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex> is assumed to be torsion free, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[Rm]]></fr:tex> is free and thus it suffices to check <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[Rm\cap  F=(0)]]></fr:tex>. But <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[rm\in  F]]></fr:tex> iff <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[r(m+F)=0]]></fr:tex>. Since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex> is finitely-generated then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[M/F]]></fr:tex> is finitely-generated and torsion. Then there exists some <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in  R]]></fr:tex> nonzero <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a\neq 0]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a(M/F)=0]]></fr:tex>. Equivalently <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[aM\subseteq  F]]></fr:tex>. Since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex> is torsion-free, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex> is isomorphic to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[aM]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
class="qed">∎</html:span></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
 
