type="machine">#293</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-293.xml</fr:route><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>12</fr:month><fr:day>18</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
type="local"
href="alex-nelson.xml"
addr="alex-nelson"
title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>There are two claims: (1) there is a factorization, and (2) the factorization is unique.</fr:p>
<fr:p><fr:strong>Claim 1: Existence of a factorization.</fr:strong> Assume for contradiction <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in  R]]></fr:tex> does not have a factorization. Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[ua\in  R]]></fr:tex> does not have a factorization for any unit <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[u\in R^{\times }]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p>We setup a set
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[S:=\{(r)\mathrel {\triangleleft } R\mid  r\hbox { does not have a factorization into irreducibles}\}.]]></fr:tex>
Assume for contradiction that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[S\neq \emptyset ]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(a)]]></fr:tex> be a maximal element of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> by <fr:link
type="local"
href="zorn's-lemma.xml"
addr="zorn's-lemma"
title="Zorn's lemma">Zorn's lemma</fr:link>. We have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> is not irreducible, so by definition we can write it as <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a=xy]]></fr:tex> where <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x,y\notin R^{\times }]]></fr:tex> are not units, so
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[(a)\subset (x)]]></fr:tex>
and
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[(a)\subset (y)]]></fr:tex>
are proper subsets.</fr:p>
<fr:p>But since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(a)]]></fr:tex> is a maximal element of a chain, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(x)\notin  S]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(y)\notin  S]]></fr:tex>, so <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[y]]></fr:tex> have a factorization. This gives us a contradiction, which means our assumption <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[S\neq \emptyset ]]></fr:tex> is wrong. We conclude <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[S=\emptyset ]]></fr:tex>. Hence we've proven the factorization of elements exists.</fr:p>
<fr:p><fr:strong>Claim 2: Uniqueness of factorization.</fr:strong> This may be proven in many, many ways. Assume for contradiction this is not true, so we may factorize
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[\prod ^{n}_{i}p_{i}=\prod ^{m}_{j}q_{j},]]></fr:tex>
where <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> is minimal (i.e., the factorization <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\prod ^{n}_{i}p_{i}]]></fr:tex> is the smallest possible factorization with fewest possible factors).</fr:p>
<fr:p>We have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n\geq 1]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p=p_{1}]]></fr:tex> divides <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p\mathrel {\bigm |}\prod  q_{j}]]></fr:tex>. Then there exists a <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[j_{0}]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p\mathrel {\bigm |} q_{j_{0}}]]></fr:tex> since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p_{i}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[q_{j}]]></fr:tex> are all prime and irreducible. Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p=uq_{j_{0}}]]></fr:tex> for some unit <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[u\in R^{\times }]]></fr:tex> (since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[q_{j_{0}}]]></fr:tex> are irreducible). Then
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[p_{1}\prod ^{n}_{i=2}p_{i}=(uq_{j_{0}})u^{-1}\prod ^{m}_{j\neq  j_{0}}q_{j}]]></fr:tex>
which implies
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[\prod ^{n}_{i=2}p_{i}=u^{-1}\prod ^{m}_{j\neq  j_{0}}q_{j}.]]></fr:tex>
This contradicts the assumption that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\prod ^{n}_{i=1}p_{i}]]></fr:tex> is the minimal factorization.</fr:p>
<html:span
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"
class="qed">∎</html:span></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
 
